<H3> <TI>   No Harm to Korean `Stability' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    No Harm to Korean `Stability' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704103794 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0942 
GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0704103794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 7 Apr (XINHUA) -- Foreign Ministry 
Spokesman Wu Jianmin said here today the maintenance of 
relaxation and stability of the Korean Peninsula conforms to the 
common interests of both the Korean people and all other parties 
concerned. "We oppose any action harmful to the relaxation and 
stability in the Korean Peninsula, be it military exercises or 
deployment of missiles." 
  He said: It is necessary to refrain from taking actions that 
will sharpen the contradictions, especially under the current 
circumstances. 
  He made the statement at a news briefing this afternoon when 
asked by reporters to comment on the fact that the United States 
has begun shipping "Patriot" missiles to the Republic of Korea 
[ROK] and that the United States and the ROK are planning to 
resume their Team Spirit joint military exercises. 
  In response to a reporter's question on the nuclear issue 
involving the Democratic People's Republic of Korea [DPRK], he 
reiterated that China has all along maintained that the DPRK's 
nuclear issue should be settled through dialogue. All parties 
concerned have expressed the willingness to settle the issue 
through continued dialogue. 

</TEXT>

