<H3> <TI>   Avoid Increasing Korean Tensions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Avoid Increasing Korean Tensions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704083694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0827 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704083694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 7 (XINHUA) -- All parties concerned 
should, in the current situation, avoid taking actions that will 
sharpen the contradictions in the Korean Peninsula, a Chinese 
Foreign Ministry spokesman said here today. 
  Spokesman Wu Jianmin told the weekly press conference that 
the maintenance of relaxation and stability of the Korean 
Peninsula conforms to the common interests of both the Korean 
people and all other parties concerned. 
  Wu said that China opposes any action harmful to the 
relaxation and stability in the Korean Peninsula, be it military 
exercises or deployment of missiles. 
  Wu said that all parties concerned should refrain from 
taking 
actions that would sharpen the contradictions in the Korean 
Peninsula, especially under the current circumstances. 
  He made the statement when asked to comment on the fact that 
the United States has begun shipping "Patriot" missiles to the 
Republic of Korea (ROK) and that the United States and the 
republic of Korea are planning to resume their Team-Spirit joint 
military exercises. 
  Wu also reiterated China's stand that the nuclear inspection 
issue should be settled through dialogue. 

</TEXT>

