<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Outlines Agenda of Song Jian Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Outlines Agenda of Song Jian Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0604114394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1128 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0604114394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 6 (XINHUA) -- Song Jian, Chinese 
State councillor and minister in charge of the State Science 
Commission, is to fly to Washington on Saturday [9 April] for a 
Sino-U.S. meeting on science and for a visit. 
  According to a spokesman of the State Science Commission, 
Song will go to the States as guest of John Gibbons, director of 
the Office of Science and Technology Policy. 
  During his stay in Washington, Song will co-chair with 
Gibbons the sixth meeting of the Sino-U.S. Joint Commission on 
Scientific and Technological Cooperation. 
  Scientific and technological cooperation weighs heavy in 
Sino- U.S. relations. 
  Since China and the United States signed an agreement on 
scientific and technological cooperation in 1979, much progress 
has been made in the fields concerned, with bilateral economic 
cooperation promoted and Sino-U.S. relations improved. 
  The agenda of the Washington meeting is understood to 
include 
a review of achievements of Sino-U.S. scientific and 
technological cooperation, intensive discussions on medical and 
health matters, environmental protection, energy and materials, 
besides probing ways for businessmen's involvement in these 
aspects. 
  The two countries will strike new protocols and renew old 
ones for scientific and technological cooperation. 
  Song will meet American senior leaders to exchange views on 
issues of common concern. 
  He will also visit Harvard University, Massachusetts 
Institute of Technology, the Ford Automobile company and General 
Motors. 
  Among the delegation are Liu Jiang, minister of agriculture, 
Yan Hongmuo, director of the National Oceanography Department, 
and Hu Qiheng, vice-president of the Chinese Academy of Sciences. 

</TEXT>

