<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Minister on Detaching MFN from `Unrelated Issues' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trade Minister on Detaching MFN from `Unrelated Issues' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK0604145294 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in Chinese 1244 GMT 
6 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK0604145294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent Xu Hong (1776 3126) ] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, 6 April (ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE)-- In an 
interview with a correspondent of this news agency, Wu Yi, 
minister of foreign trade and economic cooperation, pointed out 
today that properly solving the issue of most-favored-nation 
[MFN] status is a key premise for developing Sino-U.S. trade and 
economic cooperation. China hopes that bilateral trade and 
economic cooperation can cast off the shadow of the MFN status 
issue and achieve greater development. 
  The female minister, who will shortly head a delegation to 
the United States, said that MFN status is only a trade issue 
and trade should not be linked with other unrelated issues. 
  Wu Yi believes that the revocation of China's MFN status 
would work against the interests of all parties concerned. 
China would suffer certain damage, but the United States would 
also be hurt, and the extent of this, moreover, would not be 
smaller than for China. 
  According to data released by a relevant international 
organization, if China's MFN status is revoked, about 200,000 
people in the United States would lose their jobs; many American 
firms specializing in trade with China, especially small and 
medium-sized firms, would likely be closed down, and American 
consumers would spend $18 billion more each year buying 
substitutes for Chinese products. 
  Wu Yi said: In this way, the United States would lose China, 
a market with enormous potential. Middlemen in Hong Kong and 
foreign- invested firms engaged in the processing industry in 
China, including U.S.-invested firms, would be hit. 
  The female minister believes that the Chinese and U.S. 
governments should rise above the MFN issue and should pay more 
attention to common economic benefits. 
  She said: China's economy is developing in a sustained, 
rapid, and healthy manner, and the market is continuously 
expanding. In the next seven years, China's total import value 
will reach $1,000 billion [figure as received]. Transport, 
telecommunications, and energy -- all of them key development 
sectors in China -- are precisely where the strengths of the 
United States lie. U.S. economic sectors are facing a historic 
opportunity for developing trade and economic cooperation with 
China. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-2167 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi067_b_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-067 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Wu Yi Interview </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Reports Wu Yi Interview </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0604113794 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0833 
GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0604113794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Zhang Yijun (1728 4135 0193)] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, April 6 (XINHUA) -- Wu Yi, minister of 
foreign trade and economic cooperation, said today: China hopes 
that the United States will "take positive and pragmatic [ji ji 
wu shi 4480 2817 0523 1395]" steps to cast aside man-made 
obstacles and make joint efforts with China to push forward 
bilateral trade and economic cooperation. 
  Wu Yi will lead a Chinese Government economic and trade 
delegation to visit the United States 11-20 April. On the eve 
of her U.S. trip, she told XINHUA that China's sustained, rapid, 
and healthy economic growth and its grandiose economic 
development plan will create even more favorable trade and 
investment opportunities for U.S. enterprises. 
<H5>  The Upcoming Session of the Joint Committee on Commerce and </H5>
Trade [JCCT] Is Very Important 
  As for the purpose of her U.S. trip, Wu Yi said that the 
most 
important thing during her mission is to co-chair, with U.S. 
Commerce Secretary Ronald Brown, the Eighth Sino-U.S. JCCT 
Session scheduled for 13-14 April in Washington. 
  According to her, the JCCT session, as an annual meeting 
between the Chinese and U.S. Governments, is a most important 
occasion for discussing bilateral economic and trade relations. 
She called the session another major event following the 
Sino-U.S. summit meeting in Seattle and the talks between 
finance and foreign ministers of the two countries. 
  She revealed that during the forthcoming session, the two 
sides will discuss trade and investment policies, and 
cooperation and legal matters in such areas as information, 
energy, transportation, the chemical industry, and environmental 
cooperation. 
  During its visit to the United States, the Chinese 
delegation 
will hold trade and investment negotiation meetings in Los 
Angeles and New York on 11 and 19 April, respectively. 
<H5>  To Discuss 800 Investment Projects and Purchase Goods Worth </H5>
Hundreds of Millions of U.S. Dollars 
  Wu Yi said: The trade and investment negotiation meetings 
will be China's first large-scale trade and investment promotion 
activity to be held in the United States in the past 15 years. 
The activity is sponsored by the Chinese Ministry of Foreign 
Trade and Economic Cooperation with assistance from the U.S. law 
firm Graham and James and the U.S. Asian Association. The 
Chinese trade negotiation group will be made up of senior 
officials, experts, and business executives from eight 
ministries and commissions of the State Council, three national 
corporations, and 26 provinces and municipalities. Meanwhile, 
the ministry's four affiliated corporations, which will be in 
the United States to negotiate exports and imports, plan to buy 
U.S. goods worth hundreds of millions of U.S. dollars. 
  She said: To further promote investment and trade 
cooperation between the two countries, the trade negotiation 
group will mainly brief U.S. businessmen about China's reform, 
opening up, and economic development, and will help prospective 
U.S. investors find opportunities in China. 
  She revealed that China will offer about 800 key investment 
projects at the negotiation meetings, including the construction 
of hydroelectric and thermal power stations, highways, railways, 
airports, and wharfs; and projects in industrial raw and semi- 
finished materials for the machine-building and electrical, 
electronics, petrochemical, and metallurgical industries; as 
well as in agriculture, livestock breeding, and forestry. 
  It Is Imperative To Remove Obstacles in Developing 
Sino-U.S. Economic and Trade Relations 
  After briefly reviewing the development of economic and 
trade 
relations between China and the United States, Wu Yi said 
bilateral trade and U.S. investment in China have grown 
continuously in recent years despite some problems that have 
cropped up. 
  Since the two countries established diplomatic relations in 
1979, trade between the two countries has developed rapidly. 
According to statistics from the General Administration of 
Customs of China, bilateral trade jumped from $2.45 billion in 
1979 to $27.65 billion in 1993, an increase of more than 11.3 
times. Meanwhile, U.S. businessmen's investment in China has 
been increasing each year. As of now, the number of U.S.-funded 
projects in China exceeds 8,000, involving an agreed upon total 
investment of $11 billion, topping the list of all foreign 
investment. More than 50 of the U.S. major firms have opened 
business bases in China. 
  Wu Yi held that a major reason for the rapid development of 
bilateral trade, investment, and cooperation is the fact that 
the two economies are highly supplementary to each other. 
  However, she stressed that if the bilateral trade and 
cooperation are to develop further, the U.S. side should take 
further steps to remove man-made obstacles. The United States 
should relax controls on U.S. technology exports to China, 
resume financing for feasibility studies for projects undertaken 
by the U.S. Trade Development Agency, resume risk guarantees by 
the private U.S. Investment Company for U.S. Investment in 
China, and resume preferential loans by the American Import and 
Export Bank to relevant construction projects in China, so as to 
further tap the the potential of China's imports from the United 
States and U.S. investment in China. 
<H5>  Most-Favored-Nation [MFN] Status and China's Rejoining the </H5>
GATT 
  Touching on the issue of MFN status, Wu Yi said: This is a 
purely trade issue and it should not be entangled with issues 
with which it has nothing to do. Proper handling of MFN status 
is an important condition for the further development of 
bilateral trade and economic coopeation. China hopes to remove 
the shadow of MFN status and achieve greater development in 
bilateral economic and trade relations. 
  Wu Yi said: China has always opposed the practice of linking 
MFN status to the human rights issues, as views on human rights 
and explanations on the meaning of human rights differ from 
country to country. China and the United States have 
differences of view on the human rights issue, and they may 
discuss them through other channels on the basis of mutual 
respect, noninterference in each other's internal affairs, and 
seeking common ground while preserving differences. The two 
sides should in no way let this nontrade factor stand in the way 
of furthering the bilateral trade and economic cooperation. 
  On the issue of China's restoration of its contracting party 
status in GATT, Wu Yi said that major progress was made at the 
16th Session of the GATT Working Party on China last month. 
Most GATT members voiced support for China's "reentry into the 
GATT" orally and in action. 
  Minister Wu Yi said: During bilateral talks, the United 
States has said it will firmly support China's reentry into 
GATT. She hoped that the U.S. side would effectively fulfill 
its promise, take a positive attitude in handling the matter of 
China's reentry into the GATT, promote the course of negotiation 
for China's "reentry into the GATT," and will truly keep its 
promise and be as good as its word. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

