<H3> <TI>   Japanese Coal Terminal Loading System Contract Signed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japanese Coal Terminal Loading System Contract Signed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0604162994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1537 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0604162994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 6 (XINHUA) -- A contract was signed 
here today by the Chinese National Technical Import and Export 
Corporation (CNTIEC) and the Japanese Tomen Co. to bring loading 
and unloading equipment from Japan to the construction of the 
northern China port of Qinhuangdao. 
  Prior to the signing ceremony this afternoon, Chinese Vice- 
Premier Li Lanqing met with Kentaroo Aikawa, general manager of 
the Japanese Mitsubishi Heavy Industries, Ltd., and Yasuo 
Matsukawa, general manager of the Tomen Co., who have been here 
to attend the ceremony. 
  The equipment worth 95 million U.S. dollars is to be 
provided 
for the fourth phase of the Qinhuangdao Coal Terminal Project, 
which is one of the key construction projects of the eighth 
five-year plan (1991-1995). 
  According to the contract, China will import a whole coal 
terminal loading and unloading system, affiliated equipment and 
computer control system. 
  The project is due to be finished by the end of 1996. The 
coal transport capability of Qinhuangdao will then increase to 
90 million tons from 60 million tons. 
  The system was bought, after international bidding, by the 
CNTIEC with loans from the Japan Overseas Economic Cooperation 
Fund. The Tomen Co. won the bidding. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

