<F P=100> West Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wu Yi Holds Talks With French Counterpart </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Wu Yi Holds Talks With French Counterpart </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704103594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0934 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704103594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 7 (XINHUA) -- Wu Yi, Chinese minister 
of foreign trade and economic cooperation, met here this 
afternoon with Gerard Longuet, French minister of industry, 
posts, telecommunications and foreign trade, who is here 
accompanying French Prime Minister Edouard Balladur on a 
four-day official visit to China. 
  During the meeting, Wu said that China attaches importance 
to 
its trade and economic relations with France, and that bilateral 
economic and trade relations are in general fine since the two 
countries established diplomatic ties 30 years ago. 
  The development of bilateral economic and trade requires a 
good political environment, said Wu, adding that with the joint 
efforts of the two governments, bilateral relations have 
returned to normal, which provides favorable conditions for the 
development of bilateral economic and trade relations. 
  The Chinese minister said that the economies of China and 
France are complementary to each other. France has strength in 
the fields of communications, telecommunications and energy, in 
which the two countries share bright prospects for future 
cooperation. 
  Longuet said that the economy of China, an important nation 
in the world, has been developing quickly in recent years, 
adding that France is willing to strengthen its economic and 
trade ties with China, participate in the country's economic 
construction, especially in the fields of communications, 
telecommunications and energy. 
  The French minister also said that to further enhance 
bilateral economic and trade cooperation and create conditions 
for French enterprises to enter the China market, France will 
provide preferential commercial credits to China in the future. 

</TEXT>

