Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jiangxi Farmers Repaying World Bank Loans </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jiangxi Farmers Repaying World Bank Loans </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704073694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0703 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704073694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Nanchang, April 7 (XINHUA) -- Farmers in east 
China's Jiangxi Province who have developed agriculture with 
funds from the World Bank are paying off the loans ahead of 
schedule. 
  A provincial government official in charge of agriculture 
said that the Jihu project, with a total investment of 445 
million yuan including 60 million U.S. dollars loaned by the 
World Bank, began four years ago. It was aimed at setting up 
production bases for domestic animals, poultry and forestry and 
developing the processing industry for farm and sideline 
products. 
  To ensure the smooth operation of the project, local 
governments have offered a package of 
production-supply-marketing services for farmers. 
  One who has benefited from the arrangement is Wang Doubin, a 
farmer in Zhangshu City who borrowed 95,000 yuan in loans to set 
up a pig farm in late 1990. 
  By the end of 1992, he had sold 828 lean meat pigs and had 
38 
breeding hogs and 277 meat pigs in stock. His net income that 
year amounted to 42,000 yuan. 
  The farmer paid off all the loans within three years. 
  Wang is a typical example of 1,800 households that have 
begun 
to pay off loans ahead of schedule. 
  A survey shows that the project has enabled local farmers to 
create an annual output value of more than 600 million yuan and 
generate profits and taxes totalling 150 million yuan. 
  The annual income of farmers involved in the project 
averages 
3,000 yuan per participant, about five times that of local 
farmers. 
  By the end of last year, the project had recovered 3.134 
million yuan to go toward retiring World Bank loans. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-2187 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi067_o_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-067 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meeting on World Bank Loans Projects Ends </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meeting on World Bank Loans Projects Ends </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0704040294 Jinan Shandong People's Radio Network in 
Mandarin 2300 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0704040294 </F>
<F P=104>  Jinan Shandong People's Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Mandarin </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The provincial meeting on the general inspection of 
projects using World Bank loans ended in Jinan on the afternoon 
of 6 April. Huang Kehua, director of the provincial finance 
department, (Xin Liqun), acting head of the World Bank 
Department of the Ministry of Finance, and (Nicholas Hof), 
director of the China and Mongolia Bureau of the World Bank, 
each delivered closing speeches. 
  Under the leadership of Vice Governor Song Fatang, pertinent 
leaders of the provincial planning commission introduced six new 
projects to officials of the World Bank for possible funding 
after the closing ceremony. These six projects include: The 
environmental protection and comprehensive improvement of the 
coastal economic zone of Shandong Province; the rebuilding of 
communications facilities of the capital city of Jinan; the 
comprehensive development of water conservancy works on Huang He 
Delta; the construction of communications facilities of 
Shandong; the development of power industry of Shandong; and the 
construction of the rural well-off-type residences to the north 
of China's Chang Jiang. At present, the province has already 
applied for $1.65 billion in loans from the World Bank. Upon 
completion of these projects, the environmental quality of key 
cities, coastal open cities, and tourist cities in Shandong is 
expected to improve. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

