<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Guangdong Sets Rules To Raise Grain Production </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Guangdong Sets Rules To Raise Grain Production </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0604141794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1338 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0604141794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Guangzhou, April 6 (XINHUA) -- South China's 
Guangdong Province has taken measures to promote grain 
production. 
  In recent years, the grain output in Guangdong has seen a 
decline due to a decrease of crop-growing area. As a result, 
the imbalance between grain supply and demand is worsening. 
  Guangdong Provincial People's Congress promulgated a set of 
regulations on a minimum size for a protection zone of farmland, 
which stipulated that the total area of the farmland protection 
zone should be more than 2 million hectares. 
  The provincial government also set a target of increasing 
the 
area of the farmland protection zone to more than 2.5 million 
hectares by the end of 1997. 
  It stressed that the crop growing area, including the double 
cropping area, should be about 3.3 million hectares in the 
province and the annual grain output should be maintained at 
17.5 million tons. 
  Meanwhile, Guangdong Provincial Government and the 
government 
in some cities and counties will jointly invest in a grain 
development program for constructing 50 commodity grain bases in 
three years. 
  Jiangmen city has increased more than 20 percent of 
investment in farming production and it has decided from this 
year on to allocate 2 million yuan annually to aid farm 
production. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

