<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shenzhen Battles Illegal Financial Activities </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shenzhen Battles Illegal Financial Activities </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK0604142894 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 1210 GMT 
6 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK0604142894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shenzhen, April 6 (CNS) -- Illegal futures broking, 
speculation on foreign exchange and fund-raising have become 
rampant in Shenzhen in recent times, seriously disrupting 
economic order there and arousing great concern. 
  Information released by the Shenzhen Industrial and 
Commercial Administration shows that some unscrupulous elements 
from outside the country collaborated with others to engage in 
illegal futures broking, speculation on foreign exchange and 
fund-raising without prior authorization. The administration 
had on several occasions investigated some 230 cases of illegal 
futures broking during 1992 and 1993 alone with the seizure of a 
lot of computers and facsimile machines. Some of the suspects 
rounded up were dealt with by the judicial department. 
  An official from the administration said that it would soon 
launch a rectification of the futures market here in a bid to 
crack down on illegal futures broking and speculation in foreign 
exchange with the eventual aim of protecting the interests of 
investors, purifying the market there and safeguarding normal 
economic order. The official stressed that entities and 
individuals were not allowed to carry out futures broking 
without prior consent from the State Securities Commission and 
registration with the State Administration for Industry and 
Commerce. He added that neither were they allowed to engage in 
financial futures business or foreign exchange trading as well 
as fund-raising without the approval of the People's Bank of 
China and the State Administration of Foreign Exchange Control. 
People found in violation of these stipulations will be 
seriously dealt with in accordance with the law while those 
found breaching them repeatedly will be harshly punished and 
even will be sent to the judicial department for legal action. 

</TEXT>

