<F P=100> PRC MEDIA ON TAIWAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   ARATS Official Pledges Proper Handling of Boat Accident </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ARATS Official Pledges Proper Handling of Boat Accident </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0604134294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1323 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0604134294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 6 (XINHUA) -- The mainland will 
properly handle the boat tragedy that claimed the lives of 24 
Taiwanese tourists and eight mainlanders, said a senior official 
from the Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Straits 
(ARATS). 
  In a telephone conversation this afternoon with Chiao 
Jen-ho, 
vice-chairman and secretary general of the Taiwan-based Straits 
Exchange Foundation (SEF), Tang Shubei, vice-president of ARATS, 
said that leaders of the Chinese central government and other 
departments concerned attached serious importance to the 
accident. 
  He said Zhejiang Province had made emergency efforts to 
locate and recover the remains of the dead. The local 
authorities had also given a lot of help to the relatives of the 
victims who went to Zhejiang to settle the matter. 
  The 32 victims died on March 31 when the tourist boat they 
boarded burst into flames on Qiandao Lake in East China's 
Zhejiang Province. 
  Tang said that he understood SEF's expectations. 
  He said that ARATS had done everything it could to keep in 
touch with SEF. 
  He told Chiao that Beijing had dispatched a team of 
specialists to the accident site to conduct an investigation. 
  Tang said that such a tragedy was the last thing the two 
sides want to see, adding that there are more than one million 
Taiwan compatriots visiting the mainland every year. It was a 
rare accident, he said. 
  Chiao conveyed to Tang the concerns and opinions of the 
Taiwan public. Tang said he will forward the information to 
relevant departments. 

</TEXT>

