</HEADER>

<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Says Malaysia Supports GATT Membership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Says Malaysia Supports GATT Membership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0604140094 Taipei CNA in English 1307 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0604140094 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Bear Li] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, April 6 (CNA) -- Visiting Malaysian 
Minister of Foreign Trade and Industry Datuk Sri Rafidah Aziz 
said here Wednesday [6 April] that Malaysia supports Taiwan's 
bid to join the General Agreement on Trade and Tariffs (GATT). 
  Rifadah, however, said that Malaysia doesn't have a set 
policy on whether Taiwan or Mainland China should join the world 
organization first. Beijing has reiterated that it should be 
admitted into GATT ahead of Taipei. 
  Rifadah's visit here is part of her global efforts to woo 
investments in the Southeast Asian nation. She presided over a 
symposium on Malaysia's investment climate in the morning. 
  She also said that it's "logical" for Taiwan to become a 
founding member of the East Asia Economic Caucus (EAEC), a 
regional economic cooperation grouping proposed by Malaysian 
Prime Minister Datuk Sri Mahathir Mohamed. 
  She said that to be an EAEC member, a candidate must be 
Asian 
country that is a member of the Asian-Pacific Economic 
Cooperation Forum and Taiwan meets all these conditions. 
  In meeting Premier Lien Chan, Rafidah said that she is 
optimistic about the development of cooperative ties between 
Taiwan and Malaysia, 
  Lien in return expressed the hope that more ranking 
Malaysian 
officials would visit Taiwan to enhance mutual understanding and 
exchanges. He also asked Rafidah to forward his invitation for 
Prime Minister Mahathir to visit Taiwan. 

</TEXT>

