<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Qian Qichen Says Civil Servants Welcome To Stay </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Qian Qichen Says Civil Servants Welcome To Stay </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704104194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0944 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704104194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 7 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Vice-Premier 
Qian Qichen said here today that China would welcome civil 
servants in Hong Kong to continue to serve the public after 1997 
when China restores its sovereignty over Hong Kong. 
  Qian, who is also foreign minister, made the remarks when 
meeting with a delegation from the Business and Professionals 
Federation of Hong Kong, headed by its chairman Vincent Lo Hong 
Sui. 
  Qian said that civil servants in Hong Kong do not need to 
worry about their future after 1997. 
  However, senior officials in the future Hong Kong Special 
Administrative Region should meet the relevant requirements 
spelled out in the Basic Law, Qian said. Only a few are 
involved in this regard, most civil servants are welcome to 
continue their service, he said. 
  The vice-premier also attributed worries among some Hong 
Kong 
residents about the central government's policies towards Hong 
Kong after 1997 to the lack of knowledge of the Basic Law, in 
which, he said, most policies are clearly stated. 
  Therefore, he agreed with guests' ideas on accelerating the 
pace of spreading the knowledge of the Basic Law and even 
providing more financial support for these efforts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

