<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-067 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hubei Attracts Hong Kong, Macao, Taiwan Investors </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hubei Attracts Hong Kong, Macao, Taiwan Investors </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704062794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0609 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704062794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Wuhan, April 7 (XINHUA) -- With the launching of the 
Chang Jiang river development strategy and the Three Gorges 
water conservancy projects, central China's Hubei Province has 
become a new attraction for investors from Taiwan, Hong Kong and 
Macao. 
  Since the beginning of 1993, a total of 1,882 investors from 
the three regions have registered in the province with total 
funds of 4.1 billion U.S. dollars, bringing the total from the 
three areas to seven billion U.S. dollars, according to the 
provincial industry and ?commerce bureau. 
  The investors from Taiwan, Hong Kong and Macao are 
interested 
in industry, construction, commerce, real estate, agriculture, 
forestry, animal husbandry and fisheries in the province. 
  Their firms are located in the cities of Wuhan, Yichang, 
Huangshi and Ezhou along the Chang Jiang river, the biggest 
river in China. 
  The number of firms with investment over one million U.S. 
dollars each has reached 9. 
  Preferential policies and regulations have been announced by 
local governments to attract funds from the three regions. 

</TEXT>

