<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wei Jingsheng, Others `Outsiders' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Wei Jingsheng, Others `Outsiders' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK0704081294 Hong Kong AFP in English 0714 GMT 7 April 94 </F>
<F P=103> HK0704081294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Gilles Campion] </F>
  [Excerpts] Beijing, April 7 (AFP)--China launched a fresh 
verbal assault Thursday on its most famous dissident, Wei 
Jingsheng, warning he faced prosecution despite attempts by the 
United States to intervene on his behalf. Foreign Ministry 
spokesman Wu Jianmin told a press conference that Wei, detained 
since last Friday, "has broken the law and must be prosecuted." 
  "These people are outsiders and are cut off from the Chinese 
reality," he said of Wei and other pro-democracy agitators. 
  The arrest of Wei was "a small problem that should not be 
exaggerated," Wu said. "There are people in jail anywhere in 
the world. In China, this is so because they have broken the 
law," he said, adding: "There is no universal penal code." 
  Wei was released on parole in September, six months short of 
a 15-year prison term for his "counter-revolutionary" role in 
the 1978-79 Democracy Wall movement. [passage omitted] 
  Foreign ministry spokesman Wu derided suggestions that the 
government was "persecuting" dissidents. "It is a completely 
groundless accusation," he said. "For China, stability is 
essential for economic development and it is necessary to uphold 
order." 
  The row over Wei and other dissidents comes in the runup to 
the decision by President Bill Clinton, scheduled in June, to 
renew most-favoured-nation status for Chinese goods to the US 
market, a benefit estimated to be worth hundreds of millions of 
dollars in customs dues. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

