<F P=100> North Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Afforestation Helps Extend Inner Mongolia Forest </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Afforestation Helps Extend Inner Mongolia Forest </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0204065094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0639 GMT 2 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0204065094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hohhot, April 12 (XINHUA) -- Despite the daily 
cutting of Timber, the Daxinganlin forest zone in northern 
China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region is still extending 
owing to the region's continuous efforts in afforestation. 
  A total area of 1.84 million hectares has now been densely 
wooded in this forest zone, so far the biggest afforested area 
in China. 
  The zone, with 80,000 hectares of afforested trees ready for 
felling, has enlarged the primeval forest in the region, which 
has only 200,000 hectares of forest for cutting. 
  With its primeval forest used for felling as early as the 
1850s, it is the biggest timber production center in China. 
  Reforestation was carried out over the past four decades 
while planting trees on wasteland as well as desolated hills and 
mountains. By now 71.5 percent of the zone have been wooded, up 
11.4 percent over the figure of four decades ago. 
  Experts say that the afforestation in the zone has coped 
with 
the felling. 
  The zone, with an annual afforestation area of more than 
67,000 hectares, can provide 240 million high-quality saplings 
every year. The survival rate of the saplings amounts to 90 
percent, an increase of 36 percent over the figure of the 1950s. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

