<H3> <TI>   UN Projects Promote Gansu's Rural Development </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Projects Promote Gansu's Rural Development </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0804021994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0120 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0804021994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lanzhou, April 8 (XINHUA) -- China's northwestern 
Gansu Province has attracted a series of international 
cooperation projects in its efforts to alter adverse natural 
environmental conditions and improve agricultural 
infrastructures. 
  The projects have brought about "remarkable changes" in 
rural 
development in this region, the provincial authorities said. 
  The Guanchuan river valley in Gansu was notorious for its 
arid land, scarce vegetation, suffering from constant soil 
erosion and frequent natural disasters. 
  The World Bank extended a low interest loan of 7 million 
U.S. 
dollars in 1987 to help this place. Now 73 percent less sand 
and soil is deposited into the already silty Huanghe river by 
the Guanchuan river, thanks to the cooperation projects with the 
bank. 
  Forestry and grass cover 42.5 percent of the land in this 
region today, up from 8.5 percent in 1986. And grain production 
is increasing 4.5 million kilograms every year. 
  A local official said, "the rural population in this river 
valley have almost ended poverty." 
  The UN World Food Program provided 61.18 million U.S. 
dollars 
in aid to help construct six large irrigation projects along the 
Huanghe river. The former drought-stricken highland has been 
turned into a grain production base. 
  In 1987, the World Bank also financed what has been called 
China's most difficult and costly water diversion project with a 
loan of 123 million U.S. dollars, relieving the repeated 
interruptions caused by a shortage of funds and complicated 
geological conditions. 
  Italian and Japanese companies are participating in the 
construction. It is expected to be finished this year and to 
irrigate 13,000 hectares of land this winter. 
  To further alleviate the water problem in Gansu, the UN Food 
and Agriculture Organization and the European Community offered 
aid packages of 200,000 U.S. dollars and 3.58 million European 
currency units respectively to set up two hi-tech water-saving 
irrigation experimental zones. 
  Promoting social development has also been an important 
aspect of cooperation with world organizations in Gansu. 
  Medical bodies in the countryside in 15 counties have been 
receiving aid from the UN Population Fund, children's fund and 
some Canadian institutions. Many rural clinics have been set up 
under the aid program. 
  The World Bank loaned Gansu 20 million U.S. dollars to 
improve rural education in some poverty-stricken areas in 1987. 
China's first pilot center aided by foreign funds to wipe out 
rural illiteracy was established in Longxi county recently. The 
UN Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization provided 
25,000 U.S. dollars in aid for the center. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

