<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports New Russian Deputy Prime Ministers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Reports New Russian Deputy Prime Ministers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704175394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1701 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704175394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, April 7 (XINHUA) -- Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin named Sergey Mikhailovich Shakhray, minister of 
nationalities and regional policy, as deputy prime minister 
today. 
  Shakhray, 38, who was named deputy minister in charge of 
federal regional issues in 1991, was removed from the post and 
given his present portfolio when Russian cabinet was reshuffled 
in 1994. 
  The Party of Russian Unity and Harmony (PRUH) formed by 
Shakhray participated in Russian parliamentary elections last 
December and found its way to State Duma, the lower house. 
  Observers think that the PRUH faction in Duma, a mild 
democrat group led by Shakhray, played a key role when the State 
Duma passed amnesty in February this year. 
  The presidential press office announced that the 
presidential 
decree also stipulates that the number of deputy prime ministers 
be increased from three, decided in January when the cabinet was 
reshuffled, to six, including one first deputy prime minister. 
  Meanwhile, Aleksandr Nikolayevich Shokhin, the minister of 
economy, has recently been promoted to be deputy prime minister. 

</TEXT>

