<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman on Opposition to Team Spirit Exercises </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman on Opposition to Team Spirit Exercises </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0804005094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0040 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0804005094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 8 (YONHAP) -- China opposes any 
military exercises or missile deployment in South Korea which 
could be detrimental to the easing of tensions in the region, 
Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman Wu Jianmin said Thursday. 
  Responding to reporters' questions about the deployment of 
Patriot missiles in South Korea and the U.S.-South Korean joint 
military exercise `Team Spirit,' Wu said China opposed any 
military activity that might exacerbate strains on the Korean 
peninsula. 
  Wu emphasized that stability and the easing of tensions in 
the region are also in the interests of neighboring countries, 
reiterating China's position that the North Korean nuclear 
problem should be solved through dialogue. 
  Asked whether Beijing would send a delegation to North Korea 
for President Kim Il-song's 82nd birthday on April 15, the 
spokesman replied, "China has never sent any delegation to 
Pyongyang in connection with Kim's birthday." 

</TEXT>

