<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Resigns Over Stalled Diet Budget Debate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hosokawa Resigns Over Stalled Diet Budget Debate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0804083994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0816 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0804083994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 8 (XINHUA) -- Japanese Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa tendered his resignation today to take the 
responsibility for the stalemate in Diet deliberations on the 
state budget for fiscal 1994, caused by a persisting controversy 
over his dubious financial deals. 
  "I have told the leaders of my coalition government and an 
emergency meeting of the cabinet of my intention to resign," 
Hosokawa told a press conference at his official residence in 
Tokyo. "I have received their approval," he added. 
  Hosokawa said he bears the responsibility for the wranglings 
between the ruling coalition and the opposition camp over his 
loans from the scandal-tainted Sagawa Kyubin Co., which has kept 
the Diet budget business paralysed. 
  The announcement came only days after a media frenzy over 
reports on his joking about stepping down, which he strongly 
denied. 
  Hosokawa had refused the opposition Liberal Democratic 
Party's demand to summon his former aide to the Diet over his 
100 million yen (950,000 U.S. dollars) loan from Sagawa, and 
denied he was personally involved in a Nippon Telegraph and 
Telephone Corp. (NTT) share purchase, which he said was done by 
his late father-in-law. 
  Earlier, before the news conference, he suddenly summoned 
the 
leaders of the coalition to the premier's official residence and 
formally told them he was quitting. 
  "The reason for my decision to resign is the paralysis in 
the 
Diet," one coalition official quoted Hosokawa as telling his 
colleagues at an emergency cabinet session. 
  He also said a new problem has been uncovered about his 
personal financial management, according to TV reports. But he 
did not specify the issue. 
  Hosokawa, 56, took office last August, ending a 38-year-long 
grip on state power by the Liberal Democratic Party. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

