<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   China To Issue Yen-Based Short-Term Funds in Japan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    China To Issue Yen-Based Short-Term Funds in Japan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704151594 Beijing XINHUA in English 1311 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704151594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 7 (XINHUA) -- China International Trust 
and Investment Corporation (CITIC) yesterday signed an agreement 
with the Bank of Tokyo, enabling it to issue yen-denominated 
commercial paper worth up to 15 billion Japanese yen. 
  Under the accord, the maturities of the short-term funds 
range from two weeks to nine months. The interest rate will be 
fixed at the time of issue and the Bank of Tokyo will act as the 
issuing agent for China in the deal. 
  Hong Yun-cheng, president of CITIC Industrial Bank, said 
that 
this short-term measure may help cut money-raising costs and 
diversify China's access to the world's capital markets. 
  Hiroyuki Nakao, senior managing officer of the Bank of 
Tokyo, 
said: "China's creditability runs high in Japan. Banks and 
other financial institutions are ready to go with the cp 
[commerican papere] program." 
  This is the first time that China has moved to issuing 
commercial paper in an overseas capital market. 

</TEXT>

