<H3> <TI>   Beijing Police Arrest Dissident Xu Wenli </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Beijing Police Arrest Dissident Xu Wenli </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Zhu, Qian Deny Involvement </H4>

<F P=102> HK0804014694 Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST in English 8 
Apr 94 p 7 </F>

<F P=103> HK0804014694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By So Lai-fun in Beijing and Chan Wai-fong] </F>
  [Excerpt] Chinese Vice-Premiers Zhu Rongji and Qian Qichen 
yesterday denied they had played a role in determining the 
outcome of the Xi Yang case. They were quoted by Vincent Lo 
Hong-sui, head of the Business and Professional Federation, as 
saying during meetings in Beijing that, as executive officials, 
they would not interfere with the Judiciary. 
  Mr Zhu, also head of the People's Bank of China, denied 
reports that he had ordered a stiff sentence for Hong Kong 
reporter Xi, who was accused of stealing financial secrets. The 
Politburo Standing Committee did not discuss legal cases, he 
said. 
  The comments came as Beijing rejected calls to release more 
details on the conviction of Xi who was sentenced to 12 years' 
jail. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

