<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Patent Office Director on Implementation of Law </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Patent Office Director on Implementation of Law </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0804042594 Beijing Central People's Radio Network in 
Mandarin 2230 GMT 2 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0804042594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing Central People's Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Mandarin </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "News and Press Review" program] </F>
  [Text] The 10th anniversary of the promulgation of China's 
Patent Law was marked on 1 April. Recently, station reporter 
(Song Jian) interviewed Gao Lulin, director of the State Patent 
Office, in connection with the success China has achieved since 
implementation of the Patent Law nine years ago. Gao Lulin said: 
  [Begin Gao recording] In 1985 when the Patent Law was first 
implemented, the Chinese government accepted approximately 
17,000 patent applications. The number of applications 
increased every year. In 1993, the Chinese government accepted 
over 77,000 patent applications. Some 20 to 25 percent of all 
the 300,000 or so patent applications accepted have been 
exploited; some exploited patents have yielded very good 
economic results. The establishment of the patent (?system) and 
the popularization of the patent [word indistinct] have 
inevitably given rise to certain disputes over patent 
infringement. But China's people's courts and patent offices 
have effectively handled these disputes. According to 
incomplete statistics, by the end of last year, people's courts 
and patent offices had respectively handled 2,000 cases of 
patent disputes. Following the revision of the Patent Law and 
China's access to and coordination with the international patent 
systems, we can say provisions for patent protection as 
prescribed in China's Patent Law have basically met the 
requirements set by the World Organization for the Protection of 
Intellectual Rights as well as by GATT. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

