<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   World Bank Officials Visit Projects in Shandong </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    World Bank Officials Visit Projects in Shandong </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704111594 Beijing XINHUA in English 1029 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704111594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Jinan, April 7 (XINHUA) -- World Bank officials, on 
a visit to Shandong from April 4-6, said that the bank's 
operations in this east China province had been very successful. 
  Nicholas C. Hope, the new director of the bank's China and 
Mongolia Office, said he was very satisfied that projects 
financed by loans from the bank had been going so well. 
  On his first day in his new post, the director visited the 
expressway connecting Jinan, the provincial capital, and the 
port city of Qingdao, and an irrigation project in Qufu, the 
home of Confucius, both backed by World Bank loans. 
  He was accompanied by Pieter P. Bottelier, the bank's chief 
of mission to China, and officials from the Chinese Ministry of 
Finance. 
  Mr. Hope said he was deeply impressed by the province's 
strict management and efficient organization in project 
operations, and that the province had never delayed repayment of 
loans. 
  From 1982 to the end of last year, the World Bank had 
provided loans worth 824 million U.S. dollars on 26 projects in 
agriculture, traffic, health and education, and 16 of them have 
been completed. 
  Mr. Hope said that Shandong has great development potential 
and provides many profitable investment opportunities. He 
expressed the wish that the bank would continue and expand its 
good cooperative relations with Shandong. 
  At the end of his visit, Mr. Hope received six applications 
from the provincial government for loans for six projects in 
coastal environmental protection, traffic, power supply and 
rural housing development. The proposed loans total 1.6 billion 
U.S. dollars. 
  Mr. Hope said he would take the applications to the bank's 
Washington headquarters, and that he would personally actively 
support them. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

