<H3> <TI>   Further on Qian-Juppe Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Qian-Juppe Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0804074794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0714 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0804074794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 8 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Vice-Premier 
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen and visiting French Foreign 
Minister Alain Juppe have held talks today on bilateral 
relations, and international and regional issues. 
  Qian said the two prime ministers held very good talks 
Thursday [7 April] and had reached an extensive agreement on 
many issues while Juppe described the talks as very positive and 
constructive, saying the French side was satisfied with the 
results. 
  The two foregin ministers agreed that China and France have 
cooperated very well on the question of Cambodia and both have 
made contributions to the settlement of the issue. Such 
cooperation should continue, Juppe said. 
  Qian noted that the United Nations' actions were successful 
in Cambodia where a new government has been formed. He pointed 
out that the Cambodian issue has now been settled as an 
international issue, therefore the domestic issues are internal 
affairs of Cambodia and those issues should be settled by the 
Cambodian people themselves. Juppe shared Qian's view. 
  Qian reaffirmed China's continuing support to King Sihanouk 
as the leader of Cambodia. 
  Briefing Qian on the latest development in the Bosnia and 
Herzegovina region, Juppe said a new situation has emerged in 
Sarajevo where the residents have begun to live a normal life. 
  However, there is still a long way to go before the final 
settlement of the problems, and an overall view is needed by all 
the parties concerned, Juppe said. Qian hoped that the efforts 
for a settlement of the Bosnia and Herzegovina question make new 
progress through negotiations. 
  Qian briefed Juppe on China's position on the question of 
Hong Kong. 

</TEXT>

