<F P=100> West Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Juppe on Sino-French Relations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Juppe on Sino-French Relations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704140894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1349 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704140894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, April 7 (XINHUA) -- France's Foreign Minister 
Alain Juppe has emphasized that his visit to China with Prime 
Minister Eduard Balladur is to mainly restore political 
relations which had deteriorated between the two countries. 
  On the eve of Balladur's first official trip to China, and 
in 
an interview published here today by LE LIBERATION, Juppe said 
worsened Sino-French relations caused by France's sale of Mirage 
fighters to Taiwan should be past history. 
  He stressed that France cannot continue discord with China, 
citing economic, political, strategic and population factors, 
and he suggested that there is no great difference between their 
two foreign policies. 
  Replying to criticism that the four day visit will not bring 
a flood of new deals, Juppe said that there is no reason why 
France should not develop relations with a country as big as 
China but explained that, in his view, this was not a commercial 
trip. 
  "It is to restore political relations." he said. "Reentering 
into China's markets requires much work and needs time." 

</TEXT>

