<F P=100> North Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Beijing Fights Inflation in Food Prices </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Beijing Fights Inflation in Food Prices </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704151694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1307 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704151694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 7 (XINHUA) -- Beijing will establish 
more vegetable farms and adopt a series of other measures to 
keep prices of staple foods down, a senior municipal official 
said. 
  Li Qiyan, mayor of Beijing, told deputies attending the 
second session of the 8th Municipal Political Consultative 
Conference here that the municipal government has begun to sell 
grain and cooking oil reserves to its citizens as a way to lower 
prices. 
  The cost of daily necessities has been growing rapidly in 
recent months in the Chinese capital. 
  Last year's retail prices rose by 16.9 percent in the city 
and many members at the conference have shown concern whether 
the city can achieve the target to keep the price rise under 10 
percent this year. This target was announced by China's Premier 
Li Peng in his government work report to the recent National 
People's Congress session. 
  Zhang Liyuan, a professor at Beijing University, proposed at 
the city's on-going session that Beijing should supervise the 
prices of daily necessities item by item. 
  Prices should be checked daily, individually, on such daily 
necessities as grain, cooking oil, meat, vegetables, eggs and 
milk. Citizens should be given price check results regularly, 
according to the professor. 
  The mayor said that Beijing is to increase its investment in 
vegetable farms and adopt a series of other measures to ensure a 
booming market supply and to slow down price growth. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

