<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Investment Pact Signed With Nigeria </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Investment Pact Signed With Nigeria </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704145894 Taipei CNA in English 0750 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704145894 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Sofia Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, April 7 (CNA) -- Taiwan and Nigeria signed 
an agreement on promotion and protection of investments Thursday 
[7 April], Taiwan's first such accord with an African nation. 
  The two countries also signed an agreement on cooperation in 
export processing zone development. 
  The two agreements were signed here by P.K. Chiang and 
Nigerian Trade and Commerce Minister Melford Okilo on behalf of 
their respective governments. 
  Okilo, who arrived in Taipei Monday for a trade promotion 
tour, said Taiwan businessmen are welcome to invest in Nigeria. 
  "Nigeria spans a large area and has a huge population and 
rich natural resources," Okilo said. "We welcome foreign 
investment to help boost our economic development." 
  Chiang said Nigeria is an important country in West Africa. 
"It is also a promising market worthy of exploration by our 
businessmen," he noted. 
  Chiang said Taiwan will help the oil-rich African country 
develop an export processing zone (EPZ) in Calabar, a port city 
in southeastern Nigeria. 
  Nigeria has sent personnel to Taiwan to study EPZ 
administration and other related expertise during the past two 
years. 
  Chiang said Taiwan will use its international economic 
cooperation development fund to offer practical training for 
more Nigerian administrators and professionals following the 
signing of the EPZ cooperative agreement. 
  Taiwan does not maintain an embassy in Nigeria, but has a 
representative office in Nigeria's largest city of Lagos and a 
consulate-general in Calabar. 
  Taiwan exported U.S.$140 million worth of goods to Nigeria 
in 
1993, but no official records of imports from that country was 
available. 
  In addition to Nigeria, Taiwan has signed similar investment 
protection agreements with 11 other countries -- Argentina, 
Indonesia, Latvia, Malaysia, Nicaragua, Panama, Paraguay, the 
Philippines, Singapore, the United States and Vietnam. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

