<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Official on Xi Yang Case, Judicial Independence </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Official on Xi Yang Case, Judicial Independence </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK0804051594 Hong Kong WEN WEI PO in Chinese 8 Apr 94 p a11 </F>
<F P=103> HK0804051594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong WEN WEI PO </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report: "Zhu Yucheng Stresses That No Department or </F>
Individual Is Allowed to Interfere in China's Judicial 
Independence"] 
  [Text] Zhu Yucheng, deputy director of the XINHUA Hong 
Kong Branch emphasized yesterday that "Xi Yang's violation of 
the law is a personal act and is unrelated to normal news 
coverage by Hong Kong reporters on the mainland or to freedom of 
the press at all." 
  Zhu Yucheng said: "I mentioned three points to the gentlemen 
from the Democratic Alliance for the Betterment of Hong Kong 
yesterday: First, Xi Yang stole state secrets and violated 
China's state security laws. It is completely within the scope 
of China's sovereignty that judicial authorities try him in 
accordance with laws of criminal procedure. Second, the Xi Yang 
case involves state secrets, so no public trial was conducted in 
accordance with laws of criminal procedure. This is a 
characteristic not only of China's law, but also of the laws of 
various countries around the world. Therefore, it was legal to 
conduct a trial in camera. Third, Xi Yang's violation of laws 
was a personal act. The fact that he stole state secrets is 
incompatible with his status as a reporter. This is unrelated 
to freedom of the press or to normal news coverage by Hong Kong 
reporters on the mainland at all." 
  Zhu Yucheng also said that no unit or individual or 
government department is allowed to interfere in China's 
judicial independence. 
  Zhu Yucheng made the above remarks when attending the 1994 
Spring soiree held by the Association of Hong Kong Chinese 
Entrepreneurs at the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center 
in Wanchai last night. 

</TEXT>

