<F P=100> Northwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Coal Industry in Ningxia Gains Momentum </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Coal Industry in Ningxia Gains Momentum </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0604145694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1425 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0604145694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Yinchuan, April 6 (XINHUA) -- China's fast economic 
growth has resulted in the widespread development of the coal 
industry in the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region in northwest China. 
  Ningxia, with estimated verifiable coal deposits of more 
than 
31.5 billion tons, is one of China's coal-producing bases 
together with the autonomous regions and provinces of Xinjiang, 
Inner Mongolia, Shanxi and Shaanxi. 
  In 1993, the region turned out more than 13.5 million tons 
of 
coal and earned some 30 million U.S. dollars by exporting 
588,000 tons. 
  According to a regional government plan, its coal production 
will reach 20 million tons a year by the end of 1995, and 
production will double the present figure by 2000. 
  Experts say the booming of the coal industry in the region 
stems from the state's policy of transferring energy and 
energy-consuming industries to the northwestern part of the 
country. 
  At present, a 2.4-million-kw thermal power plant is being 
built in the region, and another 10-million-kw thermal power 
base is included under the government plan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-2316 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi068_h_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-068 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> West Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Visit by France's Balladur </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Visit by France's Balladur </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Li Peng Says Ties `Normal' </H4>

<F P=102> OW0704161394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1543 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0704161394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 7 (XINHUA) -- "China always attaches 
great importance to its relations with France," Chinese Premier 
Li Peng said in talks with his visiting French counterpart 
Edouard Balladur here this afternoon. 
  Balladur said his current China visit is aimed at improving 
French-Chinese relations. 
  According to a spokesman of the Chinese Foreign Ministry, 
the 
talks between the Chinese and French prime ministers proceeded 
in a sincere and friendly atmosphere. 
  During the talks Chinese Premier Li said: "Through joint 
efforts, China and France reached understanding in resuming 
traditional friendly relations of cooperation in January this 
year. With the publication of the joint communique between the 
two governments, Sino-French relations returned to the normal 
track." 
  Li pointed out that although the world has seen tremendous 
changes in recent years, the importance of the Sino-French 
cooperation has not been reduced, but increased. 
  The two countries, he continued, have many points in common 
in safeguarding world peace and promoting economic development. 
  Economically, Li said, the two countries are mutually 
complementary, and the potential for the development of economic 
cooperation is great. 
  He stressed that China would pursue long-term, stable and 
friendly ties of cooperation with France according to the 
principle of seeking common ground while reserving differences, 
mutual respect, mutual non-interference in each other's internal 
affairs and equality and mutual benefit. 
  Li appreciated the positive efforts Prime Minister Balladur 
and the French Government had made to restore and improve the 
bilateral ties. 
  "We should have an eye on the 21st century, and handle the 
bilateral ties strategically to make the Sino-French relations 
enjoy healthy development," Li said. 
  The premier said that China and France have bright prospects 
in developing their economic and trade cooperation since the 
economy of China has entered a sustained, rapid and healthy 
development track, thus making it possible for China to expand 
its economic and trade cooperation with every countries in the 
world including France. 
  Secondly, he said, France has advantages in the fields of 
transportation, energy and telecommunications and these sectors 
are just China's priority for development. China welcomes more 
French enterprises to participate in competition in China on the 
basis of equality. 
  Thirdly, Li said, China always take a positive attitude 
towards the development of its trade and economic cooperation 
with France. 
  He hoped that French enterprises would strengthen their 
competitiveness in the Chinese market so as to expand 
Sino-French trade and economic cooperation. 
  Balladur also believed there are great potentials for 
France- 
China cooperation. 
  He said the future visits of Chinese and French ministers 
will promote bilateral trade and economic cooperation. 
  Li and Balladur also discussed the possibilities of 
cooperation on important projects. They agreed that the two 
sides, keeping the momentum of high-level contacts, will 
strengthen political consultations and confirm the memorandum of 
consultations between foreign ministers and deputy foreign 
ministers, which was reached this January when Chinese 
Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen visited France. 
  Touching on issues of China's re-entry in GATT, Balladur 
said 
that France supports China to resume its founding party position 
in GATT, and thus become a founding nation in the world trade 
organization. 
  Li expressed his thanks for this. 
  The Chinese premier briefed Balladur on U.S. Secretary of 
State Christopher's China visit, and explained China's 
principled stand on human rights issues. 
  Balladur briefed Li on France's views over the rights issue, 
saying that France, having no intention to interfere in other 
nation's internal affairs, is willing to discuss the issue with 
other countries on an equal footing. 
  Premier Li, at the guests' request, also briefed them on 
China's independent policy of foreign affairs and its relations 
with its neighbors. 
  The prime ministers exchanged views on international and 
regional issues of common concern. They noted that they share 
views on many issues. The two sides agreed that both China and 
France are influential nations in international affairs, and 
that the maintenance of good relations between them accords with 
the fundamental interests of the two sides and the world peace 
and stability as well. 
  Among those present at the talks were Chinese Vice-Premier 
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen, Chairman of the Chinese 
Government Reception Committee and Minister of Power Industry 
Shi Dazhen, French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe, and Minister of 
Industry, Posts, Telecommunications and Foreign Trade Gerard 
Longuet. 
  Prior to the talks, Premier Li presided over a welcoming 
ceremony for Prime Minister Balladur. 
  In the evening, Li hosted a banquet in honor of Balladur and 
his party. 
  This afternoon, Zhou Jue, vice-chairman of the Foreign 
Affairs Committee of the National People's Congress of China, 
held working talks with Vice-Presidents Gilles de Robien and 
Pierre-Andre Wiltzer of the National Assembly of France. 
  Balladur arrived here this morning as Premier Li's guest on 
a 
four-day official visit to China. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

